            <tr>
              <td>8</td>
              <td><strong>Chennai Port</strong></td>
              <td>Tamil Nadu</td>
              <td>1881</td>
              <td><strong>Oldest artificial harbour</strong> on India's east coast. Operations began 1881. All-weather port with wet docks. Major automobile export hub.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>9</td>
              <td><strong>V.O. Chidambaranar Port</strong><br><small>(formerly Tuticorin)</small></td>
              <td>Tamil Nadu</td>
              <td>1974</td>
              <td>Declared 10th major port on 11 July 1974. Renamed after freedom fighter V.O. Chidambaranar. Handles salt, fertilisers, and thermal coal.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>10</td>
              <td><strong>Kamarajar Port</strong><br><small>(formerly Ennore)</small></td>
              <td>Tamil Nadu</td>
              <td>1999/2001</td>
              <td>Declared major port March 1999. <strong>Only corporatised major port</strong> in India — incorporated as a company under Companies Act, not a statutory authority. Commercial operations began 22 June 2001. Located 18 km north of Chennai. Renamed Kamarajar Port (after C. N. Annadurai's Tamil name).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>11</td>
              <td><strong>Visakhapatnam Port</strong><br><small>(Vizag)</small></td>
              <td>Andhra Pradesh</td>
              <td>1964</td>
              <td>Port opened 7 October 1933; notified as major port 1964. <strong>Deepest port</strong> among the 12 traditional major ports — natural depth 16.5 metres. Described as India's deepest landlocked and protected harbour. Handles bulk cargo (iron ore, coal).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>12</td>
              <td><strong>Paradip Port</strong></td>
              <td>Odisha</td>
              <td>1966</td>
              <td>Foundation stone by PM Nehru on 3 January 1962. Declared major port on 18 April 1966 (8th major port). <strong>First major port on East Coast commissioned after Independence.</strong> Crossed 150 MMT in FY 2024-25.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>13</td>
              <td><strong>Syama Prasad Mookerjee Port</strong><br><small>(Kolkata + Haldia)</small></td>
              <td>West Bengal</td>
              <td>1870</td>
              <td><strong>Oldest major port in India</strong> — established 1870 by British East India Company. <strong>Only riverine major port</strong> — on the Hooghly River (distributary of Ganga), 203 km from the sea. Has two dock systems: Kolkata Dock (on Hooghly) and Haldia Dock Complex (opened 1977, handles larger vessels). Renamed Syama Prasad Mookerjee Port on 12 January 2020 (150th year).</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

